Question 1:

#Importing Libraries
library(MASS)
library(ggplot2)

#Importing cats data into a data frame
cat_data<-cats
#Separating Variable of Interest
Bwt<-cat_data$Bwt

#Drawing distribution of cats bodyweight
ggplot(data = cat_data, aes(x=cat_data$Bwt))+geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.1) + xlab("Bodyweight(Kg)")+ylab("Number of cats")+ggtitle("Cat weights from Fischer(1947)")+ theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"), axis.title.x = element_text(face = "bold"),
                                                axis.title.y = element_text(face = "bold"))

ggplot(data = cat_data, aes(x=cat_data$Bwt))+stat_ecdf()

summary(cat_data$Bwt)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   2.000   2.300   2.700   2.724   3.025   3.900
  1. The minimum body weight of cats is 2kgs.The maximum body weight of cats is 3.9kgs. While, the mean body weight of cats is 2.7kgs.
  2. The mean and median of the distribution are almost similar. So it looks like an approximate normal distribution. So, the weights of the cats are approximately normally distributed

Answer 2:

#Importing American National Election Study Pilot Data
anes_pilot<-read.csv('anes_pilot_2016.csv')

#Converting Immigration Attitude to factor variable
str(anes_pilot$immig_numb)
##  int [1:1200] 2 3 6 2 1 2 1 4 3 3 ...
anes_pilot$immig_numb<-as.factor(anes_pilot$immig_numb)

#Data Cleaning
#Removing observations with missing values and feeling thermometer scores greate than 100
anes_pilot<-subset(anes_pilot, anes_pilot$fttrump<=100 & anes_pilot$fthrc<=100 & anes_pilot$ftsanders<=100 & anes_pilot$ftrubio<=100)
#install.packages('tidyverse')
library(tidyr)
library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following object is masked from 'package:MASS':
## 
##     select
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
#Feeling Thermometer scores for each of the 4 candidates
feeling_thermometer_scores<-data.frame(Trump=anes_pilot$fttrump,Hillary=anes_pilot$fthrc,Sanders=anes_pilot$ftsanders,Rubio=anes_pilot$ftrubio)
                               
#Rearranging Thermometer scores Data Frame using gather function
feeling_thermometer_scores_long<-feeling_thermometer_scores %>%
  gather(key="Candidate",value = "FtThermometer",c("Trump","Hillary","Sanders",
                                                   "Rubio"))

#Plotting Feeling Thermometer scores for the 4 candidates
ggplot(data = feeling_thermometer_scores_long, aes(x=FtThermometer, fill=Candidate))+geom_histogram(binwidth = 3)+
  facet_wrap(~Candidate, ncol = 2) +xlab("Feeling Thermometer score")+ylab("Number of Respondents") + ggtitle("Feeling Thermometer Scores of Candidates")+ theme(legend.title = element_blank(), plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"), axis.title.x = element_text(face = "bold"),axis.title.y = element_text(face = "bold")) 

#Finding Mean Feeling Thermometer Scores for each of the 4 Candidates
ft_scores<-feeling_thermometer_scores_long %>%
  group_by(Candidate) %>%
  summarise(MeanFeelingThermometerScore=mean(FtThermometer))
ft_scores
## # A tibble: 4 x 2
##   Candidate MeanFeelingThermometerScore
##   <chr>                           <dbl>
## 1 Hillary                          43.1
## 2 Rubio                            41.5
## 3 Sanders                          50.3
## 4 Trump                            38.3

1.The graph looks fairly surprising as the democarat nominee(Hillary Clinton) and Republican nominee(Donald trump) have more detractors with very cold feelings towards them as compared to their counterparts(Bernie Sanders and Marco Rubio) in their parties.
2. Also looking at their mean feeling thermometer scores, both Presidential Nominees have lower scores as compared to their fellow party counterparts whom they beat to become presidential candidates. Rubio has a higher score(41) as compared to Trump(38). Sanders has a higher score(50) as compared to Clinton(43) 3. The most surprising thing is that Trump has the lowest Feeling Thermometer scores amongst all 4 candidates. No wonder the 2016 US Presidential Elections were considered the biggest upset in US Politics since Truman won in 1948.

library(tidyr)
library(dplyr)
#Combining the immigration attitudes with the feeling thermometer scores of each of the 4 candidates into one dataframe
Question2_df<-data.frame(immig_numb=anes_pilot$immig_numb, fttrump=anes_pilot$fttrump, fthrc=anes_pilot$fthrc, ftrubio=anes_pilot$ftrubio, ftsanders=anes_pilot$ftsanders)

#Summarising Mean Feeling Thermometer scores for each immigration attitudes
Question2_df_final <- Question2_df %>%
  group_by(immig_numb) %>%
  summarise(Trump=mean(fttrump),
            Hillary=mean(fthrc),
            Sanders=mean(ftsanders),
            Rubio=mean(ftrubio))

#Rearranging Thermometer scores for each immigration attitudes using gather function
Question2_df_final_long<-Question2_df_final %>%
  gather(key="Candidate",value = "Mean Feeling Thermometer Scores",
         c("Trump","Hillary","Sanders","Rubio"))

#plotting the graphs
ggplot(data = Question2_df_final_long, aes(x=immig_numb,y=`Mean Feeling Thermometer Scores`,
                                           fill=Candidate))+ geom_bar(stat = 'identity', width = 0.6) + facet_wrap(~Candidate, ncol = 2)+ xlab("Immigration attitude(warmer to colder)")+ylab("Mean Feeling Thermometer Score(colder to warmer)")+theme(legend.title = element_blank())

  1. We can see that people who feel negatively against the immigrants(or have higher immigration attitude scores i.e greater than 5) have high feeling thermometer scores (or feel more warmly) towards the republican candidates Trump and Rubio(with an average feeling thermometer score of greater than 50). On the other hand these people with negative attitude towards immigrants feel less affinity towards Democrat Candidates Hillary and Sanders(with an average feeling thermometer score of close to just 30)
  2. Similarly, people with warmer feelings towards immigrants(people with lower value on immigration attitude) have higher affinity towards democrats(Hillary and Sanders with average feeling thermometer score of close to 60)
  3. From this graph, we can infer how Democrats in general are Pro Immigrants and Republicans in general are anti immigrants.
